WEBVTT

00:06.773 --> 00:10.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Good evening. I'm
Gwen Ifill. Judy Woodruff is
away.

00:10.410 --> 00:16.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" tonight: A
powerful earthquake rocks
Afghanistan, rattling parts of
Pakistan

00:16.016 --> 00:22.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and India as well, chaos on the
streets, as the number of dead
and injured climbs.

00:22.456 --> 00:27.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Also ahead: a meat lover's
nightmare. The World Health
Organization finds eating bacon,

00:27.761 --> 00:32.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sausage, and other processed
meats can raise the risk of
cancer.

00:32.666 --> 00:37.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Plus, Secretary of Education
Arne Duncan on reducing the
amount of testing in the
nation's

00:37.004 --> 00:38.772 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
schools.

00:38.772 --> 00:41.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ARNE DUNCAN, U.S. Education
Secretary: Where we are doing
things that are redundant, or

00:41.475 --> 00:45.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
duplicative, or not helpful,
well, that's a waste of
everyone's time and energy.

00:45.045 --> 00:49.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And going beyond the
headlines, what two teenagers'
lives tell us about the

00:49.383 --> 00:52.853 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
cycle of attacks in
the Middle East.

00:52.853 --> 00:57.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: All this
playing out amid a surge of
violence between Palestinians
and

00:57.357 --> 01:02.162 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Israelis, the story of Naor and
Ahmed a microcosm of a wider
narrative.

01:02.162 --> 01:08.902 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: All that and more
on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

01:08.902 --> 01:13.573 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

01:13.573 --> 01:23.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The death toll is
still climbing from the powerful
earthquake that struck
Northeastern

01:23.483 --> 01:30.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Afghanistan much earlier today.
At least 263 were killed, most
of them in neighboring Pakistan.

01:30.390 --> 01:35.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The quake was centered deep
under the Hindu Kush mountains,
but at magnitude 7.5, its

01:35.128 --> 01:38.832 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reach extended well into India.

01:38.832 --> 01:43.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lindsey Hilsum of Independent
Television News has this report.

01:43.403 --> 01:52.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Gilgit, on Pakistan's border
with Afghanistan, the earthquake
caused a landslide. A security

01:52.212 --> 02:01.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
camera in Mingora in Pakistan
captured the moment in someone's
garage. And the news reader

02:01.088 --> 02:12.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on Ariana TV in the Afghan
capital, Kabul, found himself
unable to continue.

02:12.599 --> 02:16.770 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Several buildings in Kabul
crumbled, even though the
epicenter of the quake was 400

02:16.770 --> 02:19.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
kilometers to the north.

02:19.439 --> 02:23.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): We
felt the earthquake. We tried to
get out of the house. It was
very

02:23.577 --> 02:28.115 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
big. The walls were destroyed.

02:28.115 --> 02:32.652 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LINDSEY HILSUM: Now there's
a danger of aftershocks.

02:32.652 --> 02:39.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Nearer the epicenter, in
Taloqan, a girls school was
struck. At least 12 students
were

02:39.659 --> 02:46.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
killed trying to rush out, while
more than 40 were taken to
hospital. People here are

02:46.500 --> 02:52.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
poor and deprived at the best of
times. Hospitals are
rudimentary.

02:52.839 --> 02:58.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the Pakistan border city of
Peshawar, several houses
collapsed. Earthquakes hit the
poor

02:58.779 --> 03:05.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
far more than the rich because
their homes are less sturdily
built. The quake struck

03:05.318 --> 03:11.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hardest in remote mountainous
areas of Pakistan and
Afghanistan. There is little
precise information

03:11.291 --> 03:15.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
yet of how many were killed or
how great the damage. Though
there is no doubt people will

03:15.529 --> 03:19.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
need help, it will be
hard to get it to them.

03:19.199 --> 03:23.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Authorities in both
Afghanistan and Pakistan say the
casualty count is expected

03:23.904 --> 03:29.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to rise as rescuers reach
more remote areas.

03:29.643 --> 03:34.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Migrants and refugees surged
across the Balkan states again
today, after European leaders

03:34.347 --> 03:40.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
held an emergency summit. Police
in Croatia said more than 13,000
people have crossed

03:40.520 --> 03:45.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
its eastern border with Serbia
within the past 24 hours. And
nearly 10,000 moved on

03:45.559 --> 03:49.529 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
from Croatia westward
to Slovenia.

03:49.529 --> 03:53.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, in Brussels, European
Union leaders said they
committed early today to bring
order

03:53.300 --> 03:55.936 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to the chaos.

03:55.936 --> 04:01.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN-CLAUDE JUNCKER, President,
European Commission: The only
way to restore order to the
situation

04:01.141 --> 04:07.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is to slow down the uncontrolled
flows of people. The policy of
waving through people

04:07.714 --> 04:13.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to neighboring countries has to
stop. I want to be clear. People
must be registrated, no

04:13.420 --> 04:16.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
registration, no rights.

04:16.823 --> 04:21.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The E.U. leaders
agreed to accommodate 100,000
people at registration centers
and

04:21.661 --> 04:24.965 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to give Greece more help.

04:24.965 --> 04:29.603 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Meanwhile, the U.N.'s
humanitarian office said today,
new fighting in Syria has
displaced

04:29.603 --> 04:35.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at least another 120,000 people.
That's more than double an
earlier estimate.

04:35.976 --> 04:41.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
An anti-migrant faction in
Poland scored big in Sunday
elections. The conservative Law

04:41.414 --> 04:46.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Justice Party celebrated
last night after winning an a
near majority in Parliament.

04:46.753 --> 04:51.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The group opposes taking in
migrants and adopting the euro
currency.

04:51.791 --> 04:56.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Conservatives in Argentina also
did well, as opposition
presidential candidate Mauricio

04:56.163 --> 05:01.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Macri forced a run-off with the
ruling party's nominee on
Sunday.

05:01.701 --> 05:06.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in Guatemala, former TV
comedian Jimmy Morales
overwhelmingly won the
presidency.

05:06.840 --> 05:11.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He attacked corruption and
promised smartphones for
children.

05:11.611 --> 05:16.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's word this evening of a
possible two-year budget deal in
Congress. House and Senate

05:16.816 --> 05:20.854 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
aides say it would allow
increased spending, despite
budget caps, but defense would
increase

05:20.854 --> 05:24.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
more than domestic programs.

05:24.057 --> 05:27.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
White House spokesman Josh
Earnest confirmed the ongoing
talks today, but said it is not

05:27.260 --> 05:29.529 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a done deal.

05:29.529 --> 05:37.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH EARNEST, White House Press
Secretary: We have worked
assiduously to protect the

05:37.571 --> 05:43.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
privacy and confidentiality of
those discussions, principally
because they're based on this

05:43.410 --> 05:47.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
principle that nothing is agreed
to in the context of those
discussions until everything

05:47.547 --> 05:52.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is agreed to. And as I stand
here today, not everything has
been agreed to. That means

05:52.686 --> 05:55.388 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that nothing at this point
has been agreed to.

05:55.388 --> 06:00.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Without a deal, the
government will run out of money
on December 11. Any

06:00.460 --> 06:03.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
agreement could also include an
increase in the federal
borrowing limit that expires
November

06:03.697 --> 06:06.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
3.

06:06.700 --> 06:12.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
An Oklahoma judge ordered a
mental evaluation today for a
woman accused of driving her car

06:12.405 --> 06:18.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into a homecoming crowd at
Oklahoma State University.
Adacia Chambers is being held

06:18.144 --> 06:23.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on $1 million bond. She faces
preliminary counts of
second-degree murder. Four
people

06:23.717 --> 06:28.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
died and dozens of others were
injured in Saturday's crash.
Chambers' lawyer denied

06:28.221 --> 06:34.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
she was drunk or taking drugs at
the time. He said she's mentally
ill.

06:34.494 --> 06:38.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Investigators in Vancouver,
Canada, worked today to figure
out why a whale watching boat

06:38.965 --> 06:44.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sank. Five British citizens died
in Sunday's incident. One is
still missing. Amateur video

06:44.871 --> 06:51.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
showed the 65-foot vessel
partially submerged late Sunday
afternoon off Tofino on
Vancouver

06:51.144 --> 06:55.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Island. Rescuers and others
rushed to the waterfront to
help.

06:55.081 --> 06:57.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSIE OSBORNE, Tofino, British
Columbia, Mayor: The outpouring
from the community has been

06:57.350 --> 07:01.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
phenomenal. And seeing the way
people come forward and they're
offering everything from

07:01.655 --> 07:09.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
food and blankets and clothing
to just people to be with people
and help them and helping

07:09.929 --> 07:11.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the ambulance, the paramedics,
the hospital staff, everything,
it's -- businesses, everybody.

07:11.765 --> 07:15.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It just comes out and
says, what can I do?

07:15.302 --> 07:20.473 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: In all, there
were 27 people on the boat.

07:20.473 --> 07:24.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Remnants of Hurricane Patricia
moved along the Gulf Coast
today. Heavy rain continued

07:24.778 --> 07:30.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from Eastern Texas to the
Florida Panhandle, and flash
flood alerts were up for several

07:30.150 --> 07:33.653 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
states. Meanwhile, Texas was
starting to dry out after the
system dumped more than a foot

07:33.653 --> 07:37.123 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of rain over the weekend.

07:37.123 --> 07:42.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The University of Mississippi
today has removed the state flag
from its place of honor on

07:42.028 --> 07:46.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
campus. The flag includes the
Confederate battle emblem, and
students, faculty and others

07:46.566 --> 07:50.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
had urged that it be taken down.
University police lowered the
banner this morning, and

07:50.570 --> 07:53.373 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
took it to the
school's archives.

07:53.373 --> 07:58.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Wall Street had trouble making
any headway today. The Dow Jones
industrial average lost

07:58.712 --> 08:05.652 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
23 points to close at 17623. The
Nasdaq rose nearly three points,
and the S&amp;P 500 slipped

08:05.652 --> 08:07.921 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
four.

08:07.921 --> 08:12.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the National Football League
is claiming success with letting
people worldwide watch

08:12.492 --> 08:18.631 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a game online for free, instead
of showing it on television.
Yahoo! streamed Sunday's

08:18.631 --> 08:24.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Buffalo-Jacksonville game in
London, and got more than 33
million views. The league says

08:24.137 --> 08:30.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the experiment proves streaming
can become the main means of
distribution for more games.

08:30.543 --> 08:36.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
the secretary of education
rethinks testing in U.S.
schools;

08:36.116 --> 08:41.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
how eating bacon might cause
cancer; an inside look at
restoring the work of Italy's
master

08:41.354 --> 08:49.929 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
painters, and much more.

08:49.929 --> 09:01.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When it comes to standardized
testing in schools, how much is
too much?

09:01.207 --> 09:07.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a policy reversal, the Obama
administration, which has
supported student and teacher
assessment,

09:07.013 --> 09:10.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now says testing has gotten out
of hand. This weekend, the White
House recommended capping

09:10.984 --> 09:14.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
testing at 2 percent
of class time.

09:14.687 --> 09:18.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A new report conducted by the
Council of Great City Schools
found the average student sits

09:18.958 --> 09:23.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for as many as 112 mandatory
standardized tests between
kindergarten and high school

09:23.696 --> 09:26.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
graduation.

09:26.900 --> 09:31.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Earlier today, I sat down with
the outgoing education
secretary, Arne Duncan, and
Michael

09:31.838 --> 09:35.742 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Casserly, the executive director
of the Council of Great City
Schools, about the problem and

09:35.742 --> 09:38.344 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the proposed solutions.

09:38.344 --> 09:43.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mr. Casserly, Secretary Duncan,
thank you very much for joining
us.

09:43.650 --> 09:47.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Secretary Duncan, you first
started talking about the
inadequacies of testing and the

09:47.887 --> 09:52.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shortfalls, the flaws two, three
years ago. What took so long for
the Education Department

09:52.425 --> 09:55.595 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to embrace this idea today?

09:55.595 --> 09:58.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ARNE DUNCAN, U.S. Education
Secretary: Well, I think we have
embraced this idea for a while.

09:58.231 --> 10:02.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's different now is we
actually have data. And I have
been talking about this, as you

10:02.035 --> 10:05.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
know, for a while, and the
president has. But what we had
were lots of anecdotes. And

10:05.939 --> 10:09.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we knew we needed to get to a
better spot, but no one had ever
surveyed the nation.

10:09.876 --> 10:15.448 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I went to Mike about two
years ago and said, would you be
willing to ask your districts

10:15.448 --> 10:16.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what to do in this space? And he
was ahead of me. He said, guess
what? We're already

10:16.249 --> 10:18.451 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
doing it.

10:18.451 --> 10:23.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's taken them two years.
It's that complicated to get
together. But now we're beyond
anecdotes.

10:23.556 --> 10:29.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have facts, and where there
is too much time spent on
testing, a redundancy or
duplicative

10:29.028 --> 10:32.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stuff, that doesn't make any
sense. And we both want high
standards. We both want good

10:32.031 --> 10:34.968 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
assessments that
drive instruction.

10:34.968 --> 10:38.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But where we're wasting students
time, where we're adding stress,
we need to challenge

10:38.037 --> 10:40.740 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that status quo. And that's
exactly what we're trying to do.

10:40.740 --> 10:46.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Mr. Casserly, some
people have already said that
the solution is not the

10:46.112 --> 10:51.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
solution. The federal government
saying you should put this cap
on testing is not the

10:51.618 --> 10:54.754 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
solution to the overtesting that
started in the first place.

10:54.754 --> 10:55.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL CASSERLY, Executive
Director, Council of Great City
Schools: Well, I actually agree

10:55.355 --> 10:57.390 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with that.

10:57.390 --> 11:04.130 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think this is a very
complicated issue. It involves
the time that's devoted to
testing.

11:04.130 --> 11:08.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It involves the quality of the
test. It involves the redundancy
of the test. It involves the

11:08.301 --> 11:14.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
use of the test. It involves all
kinds of pretty complicated
factors.

11:14.240 --> 11:20.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You might solve a little bit of
the time problem by putting a
time cap on this, but you could

11:20.280 --> 11:26.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also do damage at the same time
if you don't address some of
those other questions. So

11:26.252 --> 11:31.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if you lowered the cap to, say,
1 percent, you could still have
redundancy in the test,

11:31.391 --> 11:35.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and you could still have bad
tests. There may be less of
them. But you haven't solved

11:35.061 --> 11:37.230 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the larger problem.

11:37.230 --> 11:41.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, how do you guard
against unintended consequences,
as happened from the testing?

11:41.734 --> 11:47.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL CASSERLY: Well, I think
one of the things that all of us
have to do now is to

11:47.040 --> 11:52.378 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
have a more thoughtful
conversation about what smart
assessments would actually be
and

11:52.378 --> 11:55.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see if we can figure out some
way to coordinate this a lot
better across federal, state and

11:55.715 --> 11:58.117 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
local entities.

11:58.117 --> 12:03.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the things that was
really clear to us from the
research that we did on this was

12:03.289 --> 12:09.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that these entities don't
necessarily talk to each other.
These layers of the education

12:09.829 --> 12:16.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
apparatus don't necessarily talk
to each other. So we have plenty
of examples where people

12:16.302 --> 12:21.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were administering overlapping
tests, and kids were actually
toggling back and forth

12:21.507 --> 12:26.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from one test to another, when
it could have been solved by
just having differing layers

12:26.713 --> 12:29.682 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of government talk to each
other a little bit better.

12:29.682 --> 12:33.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Secretary Duncan,
government talking to each other
is not necessarily what
government

12:33.152 --> 12:38.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
does best. In fact, there are
people who say that part of the
overtesting was a result

12:38.191 --> 12:44.764 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of people trying to meet
standards that you were
promoting, Race to the Top,
Common Core

12:44.764 --> 12:47.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
standards, and, as a result, you
kept layering one test on top of
the other.

12:47.433 --> 12:49.102 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you feel that you might have
some responsibility for that?

12:49.102 --> 12:51.337 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ARNE DUNCAN: Oh, no,
I think we all do.

12:51.337 --> 12:55.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think, Gwen, what has been
so -- what I have appreciated so
much is, this is -- honestly,

12:55.141 --> 13:00.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this is real leadership in
action. This is our major urban
school districts coming together

13:00.380 --> 13:05.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and saying we need to do better.
This is the state chief officers
coming together with

13:05.451 --> 13:07.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us saying we need to do better.
And it's us being
self-reflective and looking in
the mirror

13:07.620 --> 13:09.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and say we want to
do better together.

13:09.689 --> 13:13.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as you know better than I,
so often, in Washington, people
just yell and point

13:13.059 --> 13:16.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fingers and they just get louder
about I'm right and everyone
else is wrong. I think

13:16.896 --> 13:20.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what we're all trying to do is
say, how do we better partner,
how do we better advice,

13:20.266 --> 13:23.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
how do we get to a better
spot for children?

13:23.202 --> 13:28.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Again, the goal here is not to
test. The goal is to improve
instruction, to improve what

13:28.107 --> 13:31.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is going on every single day for
that child in classroom. And
where we're getting good

13:31.811 --> 13:35.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
information to teachers and to
parents and to students
themselves that empower them to

13:35.481 --> 13:39.052 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
build upon strengths and work on
weaknesses, that's a good thing.

13:39.052 --> 13:41.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Where we are doing things that
are redundant, or duplicative,
or not helpful, well, that's

13:41.954 --> 13:44.190 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a waste of everyone's
time and energy.

13:44.190 --> 13:47.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, it's not just
Washington. A lot of the
movement to opt out of these

13:47.593 --> 13:52.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tests started in local school
districts and around the country
with parents, with teachers.

13:52.498 --> 13:57.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
How much of that will be
satisfied by Washington saying
do less?

13:57.270 --> 14:01.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ARNE DUNCAN: Well, I think there
are two sides of this coin,
folks who think we just need

14:01.474 --> 14:03.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do more and more testing. I
think that is wrong. Folks who
think we shouldn't do

14:03.876 --> 14:07.480 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
any assessments,
that's equally wrong.

14:07.480 --> 14:11.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there is a commonsense
middle ground here. This is very
much a civil rights issue.
Historically

14:11.417 --> 14:17.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in this nation, we swept under
the rug the horrific disparities
in outcomes, the horrific

14:17.356 --> 14:22.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
achievement gap between black
and white students and Latino
and white students and poor
students

14:22.562 --> 14:25.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and wealthier students. Too much
testing is bad. Walking away
from assessment is equally

14:25.498 --> 14:27.400 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
bad.

14:27.400 --> 14:28.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But let's find the commonsense
middle ground. I think that's
what we're all striving to

14:28.801 --> 14:30.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
do and to do together.

14:30.770 --> 14:32.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It doesn't sound
like you have figured out where
that sweet spot is, Mr.

14:32.038 --> 14:33.005 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Casserly.

14:33.005 --> 14:35.942 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MICHAEL CASSERLY: No,
we really haven't.

14:35.942 --> 14:40.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And part of our goal here was
just to gather some data on how
much testing was actually

14:40.580 --> 14:48.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
done. We haven't figured out the
right balance yet. We did
announce today that the Council

14:48.654 --> 14:53.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Great City Schools, in
coordination with Council of
Chief State School Officers,
would

14:53.292 --> 14:58.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
form a commission to start
looking at exactly what the
right balance would be, what
would

14:58.297 --> 15:03.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
models and options for school
districts be that would present
a much more rational and

15:03.102 --> 15:05.571 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
intelligent assessment system.

15:05.571 --> 15:11.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: In the meantime,
there has been a huge, I would
say, explosion of a business

15:11.377 --> 15:16.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
model which is based on testing.
Don't you anticipate pushback
from those companies who

15:16.015 --> 15:18.384 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
have been behind a
lot of these tests?

15:18.384 --> 15:23.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL CASSERLY: oh, I think
the answer to that is, yes, of
course we do. We're not naive

15:23.256 --> 15:27.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about this and we certainly
don't think that just because we
put out some data about how

15:27.393 --> 15:31.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
much testing it is that all of a
sudden the test publishers are
going to go, oh, gee,

15:31.364 --> 15:35.568 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
heavens, I never knew, we should
stop selling these tests.

15:35.568 --> 15:42.175 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't believe that for a
second. But I do think that, in
cooperation with the federal

15:42.175 --> 15:49.448 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government, the Department of
Education, the states and the
big urban public school systems,

15:49.448 --> 15:52.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we can at least start
creating a more intelligent
conversation about what it is

15:52.919 --> 15:55.254 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
we buy.

15:55.254 --> 15:58.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARNE DUNCAN: Gwen, if I could
add, I think it's just so
important part of the
conversation

15:58.391 --> 16:01.794 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is on the amount, and that's an
important conversation to have,
but that's maybe half

16:01.794 --> 16:04.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the battle here.

16:04.697 --> 16:09.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The big thing that we have to
get to is, are these assessments
high-quality? And so, for

16:09.368 --> 16:13.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
example, if folks just cut back
testing and they go to
fill-in-the-bubble tests, that

16:13.239 --> 16:17.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would be a disaster. We want
writing to be assessed. That
takes a little time. We want

16:17.577 --> 16:22.081 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
critical thinking to be
assessed, and so making sure
that there are high-quality
assessments

16:22.081 --> 16:27.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that are available in real time,
the results, to teachers, to
parents, to students, so that,

16:27.153 --> 16:30.590 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
again, instruction improves on
a daily, on a weekly basis.

16:30.590 --> 16:33.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: How do you measure
effectiveness? That's the other
piece of this. It's one thing

16:33.993 --> 16:37.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to have quality. It's another
thing to have quantity.

16:37.163 --> 16:41.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But then you have to be able to
measure that learning has
actually approved. And that's

16:41.033 --> 16:45.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been the defense which testers
have used, which is we need to
have that basic line.

16:45.471 --> 16:48.608 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ARNE DUNCAN: I think the world
is changing and it's really
important.

16:48.608 --> 16:53.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Historically, Gwen, as you know,
you had 50 different states
doing 50 different tests,

16:53.546 --> 16:56.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which you couldn't compare and
frankly cost a heck of a lot
more money because everyone

16:56.148 --> 17:01.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was doing their own thing. And
what you now have, again, thanks
to Mike's leadership and

17:01.387 --> 17:04.657 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the state chief officers and
others' leadership, governors'
leadership, is you have more and

17:04.657 --> 17:07.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
more states starting
to work together.

17:07.426 --> 17:11.564 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so the real key in all this,
Gwen, is how do we accelerate
the pace of change? Who

17:11.564 --> 17:16.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is doing a fantastic job with
English-language learners? Who
is doing a great job in rural

17:16.402 --> 17:19.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
communities, or in inner-city
communities, or in Native
American reservations and how

17:19.372 --> 17:23.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
do we replicate and share what
is working and scale those best
practices?

17:23.009 --> 17:25.578 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And you think
it can be effective?

17:25.578 --> 17:27.246 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ARNE DUNCAN: I know
it can be effective.

17:27.246 --> 17:31.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I visit schools all --
probably more schools than
almost anybody across 50 states
and I

17:31.751 --> 17:36.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see extraordinary work. We met
with two teachers earlier today
who talked about how the data

17:36.289 --> 17:40.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they're getting is helping them
not to teach to 25 or 30
students in aggregate, but to

17:40.559 --> 17:44.297 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
teach individually, personalized
way -- in a personalized way to
every single child and

17:44.297 --> 17:46.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
help them get to where
they need to go.

17:46.966 --> 17:53.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a lot of learning to do
going forward, but great
assessments actually improve
instruction,

17:53.506 --> 17:56.909 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
drive right teaching and
learning, are not in conflict
with it. We just have to make

17:56.909 --> 17:59.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that more the norm and
not the exception.

17:59.478 --> 18:01.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Secretary Arne
Duncan, Michael Casserly, thank
you both very much.

18:01.480 --> 18:01.948 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL CASSERLY: Thank you.

18:01.948 --> 18:07.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ARNE DUNCAN: Thank you.

18:07.353 --> 18:18.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: We return now to the
violence that's lately consuming
Israel and the Palestinian

18:18.364 --> 18:20.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
territories.

18:20.700 --> 18:27.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we focus on one single
event involving two young
teenage boys on October 12, an
episode

18:27.707 --> 18:33.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which has triggered more anger
and response than any of the
others in the latest wave.

18:33.079 --> 18:38.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"NewsHour" special correspondent
Martin Seemungal returned to the
scene to find out more about

18:38.417 --> 18:42.388 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
happened, and how it has
affected the already fractured
relationship between local
Israelis

18:42.388 --> 18:44.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and Palestinians.

18:44.523 --> 18:48.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
A warning: This report
contains some graphic images.

18:48.427 --> 18:54.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: The scenes on
this street are calm, giving no
indication of the violence

18:54.734 --> 19:01.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that happened here. The video is
too graphic to show: a
13-year-old boy on the ground
bleeding.

19:01.640 --> 19:07.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The boy is Ahmed Manasra, a
Palestinian. The story leading
up to this shocking moment is

19:07.013 --> 19:09.782 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as disturbing as the video.

19:09.782 --> 19:12.284 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
EYAL ELBAZI, Witness: He stabbed
a little kid right here.

19:12.284 --> 19:16.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Police have
accused Ahmed and his
15-year-old cousin Hassan of
stabbing

19:16.822 --> 19:23.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
two Israelis, one also 13 years
old. Police released
closed-circuit video footage of
what

19:23.729 --> 19:30.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they say are Ahmed and Hassan
running from the scene armed
with knives. Minutes later,

19:30.302 --> 19:34.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
another camera shows Hassan
lunging across the train tracks
at police, before he is shot

19:34.407 --> 19:37.376 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and killed.

19:37.376 --> 19:40.679 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ahmed is pursued by police
and a furious crowd.

19:40.679 --> 19:44.417 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Eyal Elbazi was in that crowd.

19:44.417 --> 19:48.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EYAL ELBAZI: What can you do?
You see him running up to that
area that there's a lot

19:48.888 --> 19:52.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of people over there. We thought
he is running out stabbing more
people.

19:52.792 --> 19:57.196 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: They caught
him at the train tracks.

19:57.196 --> 20:01.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
According to the initial
reports, Ahmed wound up here on
the tracks because he was hit by

20:01.700 --> 20:07.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a car, but the Israeli doctors
who treated him say his injuries
fit the profile of someone

20:07.440 --> 20:12.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who had been struck by a blunt
instrument. We may never know,
but we do know that the

20:12.011 --> 20:17.750 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
video triggered widespread
anger among Palestinians.

20:17.750 --> 20:23.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It went viral on social media.
The cell phone video, recorded
by an Israeli bystander, was

20:23.589 --> 20:28.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
viewed millions of times on
Facebook, complete with
background sound of people
cursing at

20:28.227 --> 20:32.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
him. His father, Saleh, says
it was unbearable to watch.

20:32.798 --> 20:38.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SALEH MANASRA, Father (through
translator): A policeman kicked
him on the leg twice. A

20:38.370 --> 20:42.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
second Israeli called him names.
The third was calling, "Kill
him, kill him." If it was

20:42.675 --> 20:46.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a cat or a dog on the road, you
would help it. He was a child.
No one helped him.

20:46.979 --> 20:50.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Mysone
Mahane MD-BO is Ahmed's aunt.

20:50.282 --> 20:56.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MYSONE MAHANE, Aunt: I was very
shocked when I saw the picture.
This is the first picture

20:56.021 --> 21:00.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we have seen. We were very
shocked. Yes, I cried. Of
course, I cried.

21:00.493 --> 21:05.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: But Elbazi
says the video didn't tell the
whole story.

21:05.798 --> 21:14.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EYAL ELBAZI: After one or two
guys was trying to stop him with
a knife and his craziness,

21:14.306 --> 21:18.477 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they beat him up a little bit.
Yes, they beat him up, but a lot
of Israelis stopped them

21:18.477 --> 21:21.447 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to -- enough, enough, enough,

21:21.447 --> 21:26.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: And Elbazi
points out that Ahmed did
receive medical treatment along

21:26.018 --> 21:32.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with the 13-year-old Jewish boy
he allegedly stabbed. That boy,
simply known as Naor -- his

21:32.725 --> 21:36.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
full name hasn't been released
-- stumbled away from the scene
and collapsed before paramedics

21:36.829 --> 21:39.465 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
stabilized him.

21:39.465 --> 21:43.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His family declined to be
interviewed. But we spoke to
others who know him, including

21:43.435 --> 21:45.638 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his classmates.

21:45.638 --> 21:50.342 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DANIEL, Friend (through
translator): He is a fine boy, a
good boy, very sociable, very

21:50.342 --> 21:54.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
friendly. He loves everyone. We
are his friends. He is in our
class.

21:54.813 --> 21:58.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Well-known to
the shopkeepers in the
neighborhood, Gil Tzemach says
he came

21:58.484 --> 22:01.453 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to his store often.

22:01.453 --> 22:05.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GIL TZEMACH, Shopkeeper (through
translator): I feel pain for the
victim for a boy who basically

22:05.291 --> 22:09.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just came to buy some candy. It
could have been me 20 seconds
before or after.

22:09.962 --> 22:14.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Ahmed is also
described as quiet and
well-liked. His mother showed

22:14.333 --> 22:20.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
us these pictures. He is fond of
animals, keeps pets, a turtle,
and pigeons. None of

22:20.806 --> 22:25.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his friends or family believe
Ahmed attacked 13-year-old Naor
with a knife, especially

22:25.411 --> 22:27.846 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his father.

22:27.846 --> 22:31.317 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SALEH MANASRA (through
translator): A 13-year-old boy
is not able to stab anyone. He
is not

22:31.317 --> 22:33.485 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
