brighter than their parents'.

24:49.855 --> 24:54.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BOY (through translator): Our
friend Naor was exactly the same
age as the Palestinian

24:54.126 --> 24:58.497 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
kid who stabbed him. Now
I hate Arabs even more.

24:58.497 --> 25:02.901 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NOAM, Israel (through
translator): I felt like
grabbing a knife and stabbing
Arabs as

25:02.901 --> 25:07.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
revenge. My friend did nothing.
He was on his way back home on a
bike. And then when

25:07.506 --> 25:11.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I saw the attacker injured, I
felt good watching him being
injured. I'm not against all
Arabs,

25:11.443 --> 25:14.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
just bad Arabs who commit
terrorist attacks.

25:14.713 --> 25:19.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: The evening of
the incident, Israeli police
raided the Manasra home in

25:19.618 --> 25:26.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Beit Hanina, confiscating phones
and belongings. Ahmed's cousin
was arrested.

25:26.024 --> 25:31.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Two nights later, police
returned, following up on
reports that Palestinians in
Beit Hanina

25:31.196 --> 25:36.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were throwing rocks at cars
entering Pisgat Ze'ev. The
police commander delivered a
very

25:36.668 --> 25:42.174 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
clear message to Ahmed's
extended family gathered in the
courtyard.

25:42.174 --> 25:47.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): If
another person comes out and
throws a stone or a bottle onto

25:47.980 --> 25:52.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the road, everyone who is
standing here, I promise, I will
break his arms and legs.

25:52.151 --> 25:56.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: The stabbing
incident also led to acrimony at
the highest levels. At

25:56.688 --> 26:02.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one point, Palestinian leader
Mahmoud Abbas accused Israel of
executing young Palestinians,

26:02.861 --> 26:08.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
referencing the video of Ahmed
lying on the ground as evidence,
prompting a swift and

26:08.801 --> 26:13.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
angry response from Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.

26:13.305 --> 26:19.645 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He accused Abbas of incitement
and produced a video showing
Ahmed being fed in his hospital

26:19.645 --> 26:25.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bed. Ahmed's family said their
lawyer was the one feeding him.
Tareq Barghout says he

26:25.350 --> 26:29.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was feeding Ahmed Jell-O when
someone from Prime Minister
Netanyahu's office arrived.

26:29.988 --> 26:34.359 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
TAREQ BARGHOUT, Attorney
(through translator): I felt
disgusted. I put on Facebook,
look,

26:34.359 --> 26:38.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the battle is now in the media.
It's not legal. They violated
the law. It's illegal to publish

26:38.263 --> 26:40.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a photo of a minor
while he is detained.

26:40.866 --> 26:44.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Dr. Asher
Salmon is the deputy director of
the hospital where Ahmed

26:44.570 --> 26:46.872 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was treated.

26:46.872 --> 26:49.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. ASHER SALMON, Hospital
Deputy Director: In general, I
would prefer that minors
wouldn't

26:49.675 --> 26:55.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be videotaped, would not -- and
pictures wouldn't be discharged.
But in a condition when false

26:55.180 --> 27:01.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
data is spread all over the
world that this kid was
executed, killed, whatever, so I
think

27:01.753 --> 27:05.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it had put things in
the proper context.

27:05.123 --> 27:10.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Hadassah
Hospital in Ein Kerem in
Jerusalem prides itself for
treating

27:10.462 --> 27:15.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all patients equally, Israelis
and Palestinians. Dr. Salmon
says they were criticized by
some

27:15.767 --> 27:18.003 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for treating Ahmed.

27:18.003 --> 27:22.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. ASHER SALMON: I did hear
words like, why do you treat
terrorists? Terrorists should

27:22.474 --> 27:26.678 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be killed, and things like that
which, of course, I am not even
going to respond to

27:26.678 --> 27:29.381 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
these type of comments.

27:29.381 --> 27:35.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: The same
policy exists at the Hadassah
Hospital on Mount Scopus, where

27:35.087 --> 27:40.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
13-year-old Naor is being
treated. In fact, Naor's lead
doctor is Arab-Israeli, the one

27:40.325 --> 27:42.895 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
who took the father
to his son's bedside.

27:42.895 --> 27:47.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DR. AHMED EID, Hadassah
Hospital: He knew because I told
him. I am Ahmed Eid, my name.

27:47.966 --> 27:53.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I guess that he figured that I
am not Jew, I am Arab. So, it
was clear to him.

27:53.105 --> 27:54.406 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: And
there were no issues?

27:54.406 --> 27:56.742 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DR. AHMED EID: No. No.

27:56.742 --> 28:01.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Ilanit Tal is
the head nurse on the ward where
Naor is being treated. She

28:01.647 --> 28:06.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
says it is a mixed staff and
this recent wave of violence is
particularly painful to deal

28:06.118 --> 28:08.020 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
with.

28:08.020 --> 28:13.926 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ILANIT TAL, Nurse: I'm used to
this attack in Jerusalem, but
not with children. It's

28:13.926 --> 28:17.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
difficult to see that -- the
children attacking us, it's
difficult, you know, and
children

28:17.796 --> 28:22.834 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
being hurt, it's not
-- it's different.

28:22.834 --> 28:28.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Naor is no
longer in critical condition and
is expected to be discharged

28:28.373 --> 28:35.781 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from hospital next week. Ahmed
was released from hospital, but
remains under arrest. Police

28:35.781 --> 28:40.786 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are treating him as a terrorist
an, he is expected to be charged
with attempted murder.

28:40.786 --> 28:57.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Martin Seemungal in Jerusalem.

28:57.736 --> 28:59.972 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Stay with us.

28:59.972 --> 29:04.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Coming up on NewsHour": some
presidential campaigns ramp up,
while others scale back;

29:04.977 --> 29:09.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and what it takes to bring new
life to centuries-old
masterpieces.

29:09.748 --> 29:15.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, first, as you have probably
heard in a headline or two by
now, it was a sobering

29:15.320 --> 29:18.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
day for meat lovers, especially
in a country that ranks second
in the world for eating

29:18.790 --> 29:21.727 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the most meat.

29:21.727 --> 29:26.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
William Brangham has the story
and some perspective on what you
need to know.

29:26.031 --> 29:30.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This new
report released today by the
World Health Organization found

29:30.469 --> 29:35.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that often-beloved meats, like
sausage, bacon, ham, and hot
dogs, can cause certain types

29:35.941 --> 29:40.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of cancer. Prior studies had
established similar connections,
but the WHO is the most
prominent

29:40.712 --> 29:45.417 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
health organization to
specifically say processed meats
can cause cancer.

29:45.417 --> 29:49.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It looked at more than 800
studies around the world. It
also found that eating freshly

29:49.821 --> 29:54.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
prepared red meat like steak or
pork or lamb probably can cause
cancer as well.

29:54.960 --> 29:59.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here to help us sort through
this is Jonathan Schoenfeld. He
is a professor of radiation

29:59.131 --> 30:03.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
oncology at Harvard Medical
School, He co-wrote a notable
paper for "The American Journal

30:03.502 --> 30:07.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Clinical Nutrition" in 2012
about the links between diet and
cancer.

30:07.339 --> 30:11.176 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Dr. Schoenfeld, thank
you for doing this.

30:11.176 --> 30:16.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The WHO certainly put the scare
into meat eaters all over the
country today. How much

30:16.314 --> 30:19.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of this -- if I'm someone who
has a couple of slices of bacon
or a turkey sandwich a

30:19.551 --> 30:23.121 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
few times a week, how
worried should I be?

30:23.121 --> 30:25.323 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DR. JONATHAN SCHOENFELD,
Harvard Medical School: Sure.

30:25.323 --> 30:29.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I Think it's important to
realize that what the World
Health Organization was, like

30:29.528 --> 30:35.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you said, as looked at hundreds
of studies and put the evidence
from those studies together

30:35.734 --> 30:40.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to show that the consumption of
processed or red meats was quite
possibly associated

30:40.872 --> 30:44.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with an increased risk of a
variety of different types of
cancer.

30:44.876 --> 30:51.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, what these studies did was
look at the overall risk of
cancer. And so it's hard to

30:51.316 --> 30:57.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say that any one piece of bacon,
for example, or piece of meat
would increase your risk

30:57.355 --> 31:02.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of cancer by a certain amount,
but, in total, you know, these
studies show that being one

31:02.260 --> 31:06.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the people who consume the
most amounts of meats or
processed foods could
potentially

31:06.064 --> 31:08.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
increase your risk
of these cancers.

31:08.467 --> 31:10.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, let's
break this down a little bit.
When we say processed meats,

31:10.869 --> 31:12.804 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what are we talking about?

31:12.804 --> 31:17.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. JONATHAN SCHOENFELD: So,
it's actually a definition that
encompasses a variety of

31:17.042 --> 31:22.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
different ways to add flavor
or to help preserve the meats.

31:22.147 --> 31:26.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the different studies that
the World Health Organization
looked at might have had a
slightly

31:26.485 --> 31:31.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
different definition of what
processed meats meant. So it
could be things like salting,

31:31.690 --> 31:34.760 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it could be things like adding
chemicals to help preserve the
food, or to help add flavor

31:34.760 --> 31:37.462 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to these different foods.

31:37.462 --> 31:40.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Is it the
process of processing itself
that causes the problems or is
it the

31:40.932 --> 31:43.201 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
cooking of processed meats?

31:43.201 --> 31:46.905 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DR. JONATHAN SCHOENFELD:
You really couldn't say.

31:46.905 --> 31:53.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the authors of this report
admit as much. What they could
look at is the total. The

31:53.011 --> 31:58.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
act of processing the meat or
the consumption of the processed
meat was associated with

31:58.183 --> 32:02.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an increased risk of cancer, but
the studies don't allow you to
actually dissect that further

32:02.587 --> 32:08.026 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and figure out what exactly it
is about processed meats that
may lead to the increased risk.

32:08.026 --> 32:12.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I know a lot
of people in the attempt to be
-- to lead a healthier life

32:12.831 --> 32:16.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and eat healthier foods have
switched to things like chicken
and turkey.

32:16.635 --> 32:20.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If those meats are processed, do
those same risks come along with
them?

32:20.038 --> 32:25.277 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. JONATHAN SCHOENFELD: It's
something that's unknown.

32:25.277 --> 32:30.482 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There is certainly some
rationale to think that that
might be the case, but these
studies

32:30.482 --> 32:34.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
specifically looked at the
processing of red meat and
whether or not that posed an
increased

32:34.186 --> 32:36.488 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
risk of these types of cancers.

32:36.488 --> 32:40.926 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, my
understanding is that the WHO
has now put processed meats in

32:40.926 --> 32:46.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the same category as cigarettes.
And we have seen some headlines
today asking, basically,

32:46.531 --> 32:50.836 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is eating a hot dog now
like smoking a cigarette?

32:50.836 --> 32:54.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Help me understand that. What is
the level of risk here? Or is
that outlandish to say?

32:54.906 --> 32:58.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. JONATHAN SCHOENFELD: Yes, I
think that's a very important
point.

32:58.710 --> 33:04.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The World Health Organization
classifies things into their
risk categories based upon the

33:04.349 --> 33:10.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
level of evidence, and not upon
the magnitude of risk. So while
it may be in the same category

33:10.922 --> 33:16.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as cigarette smoking, the
magnitude of the risk associated
with processed meats doesn't

33:16.094 --> 33:21.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nearly compare to the magnitude
of risk that's been found with
cigarette smoking.

33:21.299 --> 33:25.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What that determination just
means is that there are numerous
studies that have found

33:25.570 --> 33:33.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
similar findings. The risk --
the relative risk for smoking is
much higher, and unlike

33:33.311 --> 33:37.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the consumption of meats, the
consumption of excess cigarettes
or tobacco doesn't provide

33:37.883 --> 33:39.050 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
any nutritional benefits.

33:39.050 --> 33:42.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I see.

33:42.254 --> 33:46.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How comfortable are you with the
strength of this science? I
mean, the industry and

33:46.825 --> 33:52.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some other scientists have said
that the WHO might be
overstating the case a little
bit.

33:52.030 --> 33:56.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How strong do you feel that this
is really a concern we all ought
to be worried about?

33:56.001 --> 33:59.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. JONATHAN SCHOENFELD: Yes, I
think it's important to
understand the strengths and

33:59.137 --> 34:03.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
limitation of this type of study
and this type of recommendation.

34:03.642 --> 34:09.714 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think we can have more
confidence in the results
because the methodology that is
used

34:09.714 --> 34:15.553 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is looking at not one study by
itself, but the aggregate
findings of many and, indeed,

34:15.553 --> 34:20.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hundreds of studies. But it's
important to realize that the
magnitude of the effects

34:20.191 --> 34:26.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the absolute increase in
risk with the excess consumption
of processed meats, of

