43:38.716 --> 43:44.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: Oh, that moment
that you talked about, too. It
was just -- it was so emotional.

43:44.222 --> 43:51.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, also, I think that he was
watching the reports, that he
was paying attention to what

43:51.229 --> 43:53.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we were saying about whether
he was going to run or not.

43:53.431 --> 43:54.999 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

43:54.999 --> 43:57.935 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: He was annoyed by
it. And he thought, they're all
getting it wrong, because,

43:57.935 --> 44:00.271 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
apparently, he hadn't
made up his mind.

44:00.271 --> 44:02.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And so he decided to
get it right. It was a very
effective and interesting way

44:02.373 --> 44:02.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to do it.

44:02.907 --> 44:04.141 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AMY WALTER: Yes.

44:04.141 --> 44:07.178 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Amy Walter, Tamara
Keith, thank you all.

44:07.178 --> 44:08.479 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

44:08.479 --> 44:13.885 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Go have some meat.

44:13.885 --> 44:14.919 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

44:14.919 --> 44:19.390 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AMY WALTER: Yes.

44:19.390 --> 44:24.862 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Finally tonight, a
story of a historic flood and
bringing together ancient

44:24.862 --> 44:29.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
craft and modern science
to restore masterworks.

44:29.634 --> 44:35.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown reports from
Florence, Italy, for his ongoing
series Culture at Risk.

44:35.773 --> 44:44.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: An artwork
brought back to life after
nearly 50 years. This is one of

44:44.015 --> 44:50.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
five wood panels comprising
Giorgio Vasari's Last Supper, a
massive painting, some
21-feet-long

44:50.755 --> 44:55.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in all, first completed in 1546,
and now, after many thought it
impossible, approaching

44:55.960 --> 44:58.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a complete restoration.

44:58.396 --> 45:02.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CECILIA FROSININI, Opificio
delle Pietre Dure: This is
probably the only place where
you

45:02.066 --> 45:05.202 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can expect a miracle.

45:05.202 --> 45:11.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Cecilia Frosinini
is overseeing the reconstruction
of The Last Supper at the

45:11.008 --> 45:17.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Opificio delle Pietre Dure, the
OPD, in Florence, Italy, one of
the world's foremost institutes

45:17.481 --> 45:23.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of art preservation and
restoration and a place itself
forged by tragedy.

45:23.254 --> 45:28.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's hard to imagine today, but,
in 1966, this famous piazza and
much of Florence was

45:28.993 --> 45:32.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
underwater, with devastating
consequences for the art
treasures for which this city

45:32.363 --> 45:33.764 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is so renowned.

45:33.764 --> 45:36.734 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
NARRATOR: It all
started suddenly.

45:36.734 --> 45:43.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: November 1966,
days of rain swelled the Arno
River, sending water, oil

45:43.741 --> 45:54.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and sediment into Florence, in
the city's worst flood in nearly
400 years. It was captured

45:54.051 --> 45:58.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in this documentary by filmmaker
Franco Zeffirelli, narrated by
actor Richard Burton and
broadcast

45:58.923 --> 46:01.926 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on Italian state television.

46:01.926 --> 46:08.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
More than 30 people died and
thousands of priceless works of
art and manuscripts were

46:08.165 --> 46:14.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
damaged or destroyed. The
disaster inspired an outpouring
of support from around the
world,

46:14.005 --> 46:18.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
enlisting donations and young
volunteers, known as Mud Angels,
to descend upon the city

46:18.576 --> 46:21.012 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to help clean up the mess.

46:21.012 --> 46:24.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
LUDOVICA SEBREGONDI, Art
Historian, Santa Croce Church
(through translator): Here, the

46:24.815 --> 46:28.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
water reached nearly 20 feet. It
was so shocking. And with the
water came damage. It moved
everything

46:28.719 --> 46:30.821 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
everywhere.

46:30.821 --> 46:36.360 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Ludovica
Sebregondi is an art historian
at the Santa Croce Church, which

46:36.360 --> 46:41.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sits just a few blocks from the
river. Parts of the church and
its famed museum were completely

46:41.999 --> 46:46.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
submerged, including where
Vasari's Last Supper hung. It
remained underwater for more
than

46:46.003 --> 46:49.407 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
48 hours.

46:49.407 --> 46:55.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Another victim, a huge crucifix
by Cimabue completed in the 13th
century, its paint almost

46:55.446 --> 47:01.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
completely washed away by the
waters. The damaged crucifix has
returned, as have many

47:01.352 --> 47:06.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other works, this time to the
museum's higher ground, in case
the waters should return.

47:06.691 --> 47:10.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LUDOVICA SEBREGONDI (through
translator): Many of the
artworks have been restored in

47:10.227 --> 47:14.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
these 50 years, but one has yet
to be returned. The most famous
of all is The Last Supper

47:14.331 --> 47:18.035 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
by Vasari. It's a
symbol of the flood.

47:18.035 --> 47:23.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A symbol because
of its size and the extent of
its damage. After the waters

47:23.641 --> 47:28.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
receded, Vasari's work was
covered with sheets of fine
paper, in an emergency measure
to

47:28.879 --> 47:33.651 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
prevent the paint from
separating from the wood. That
bought time, but for more than

47:33.651 --> 47:37.321 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
40 years, few believed it
could be saved in one piece.

47:37.321 --> 47:42.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CECILIA FROSININI: Many of the
old restorers advised that,
basing on their experience,

47:42.126 --> 47:47.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
based on their experience, the
only possible way was to destroy
the wood or at least to

47:47.131 --> 47:52.169 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
try to preserve the wood,
but to separate in two.

47:52.169 --> 47:57.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A decision was
made to wait, until new
restoration methods gave OPD
officials

47:57.208 --> 48:01.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
confidence they could preserve
it in its original form.

48:01.412 --> 48:09.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in 2009, the work began.
The OPD, whose name translates
to the Workshop of Semi-Precious

48:09.520 --> 48:16.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Stones, has a storied history
itself. Dating to the 16th
century under the Medici family,

48:16.260 --> 48:21.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it produced the finest inlaid
mosaic and stonework, using
techniques that can still be
found at

48:21.198 --> 48:24.001 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
its museum workshop
in Florence today.

48:24.001 --> 48:30.007 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the 20th century, it turned
to conservation, and, expanding
into a Renaissance-era fort

48:30.007 --> 48:34.812 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
after the 1966 flood, it
dramatically broadened its
mission and scope.

48:34.812 --> 48:37.815 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
OPD director Marco Ciatti:

48:37.815 --> 48:42.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCO CIATTI, Director, Opificio
delle Pietre Dure: We needed new
techniques. Mainly, the

48:42.219 --> 48:46.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
flood was the starting point
with the new relationship with
science.

48:46.590 --> 48:52.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Around every
corner, a work by one master or
another, a Botticelli sitting

48:52.062 --> 48:58.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on an easel, Leonardo da Vinci's
Adoration of the Magi, usually
in Florence's Uffizi

48:58.402 --> 49:04.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Museum, awaiting a cleaning, and
more recent works, an early
Jackson Pollock that's just

49:04.408 --> 49:09.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
arrived. It's part museum, part
workshop, part hospital for
threatened treasures.

49:09.580 --> 49:13.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TON WILMERING, Getty Foundation:
The dark areas are less dense,
so that's where paint

49:13.884 --> 49:17.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has been lost, and you can very
clearly see the splits between
the planks.

49:17.888 --> 49:23.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Ton Wilmering, an
expert in wood restoration,
showed me a large X-ray

49:23.160 --> 49:28.899 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
image of part of the Vasari.
Wilmering is with the Getty
Foundation, which helped fund

49:28.899 --> 49:31.836 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Vasari project.

49:31.836 --> 49:35.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the record, the Getty Trust
supports the "NewsHour"'s arts
coverage.

49:35.406 --> 49:39.210 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TON WILMERING: And when the
water receded, it pulled some of
the paint, it pulled some

49:39.210 --> 49:42.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the gesso, which is the layer
in between the wood panel and
the paint, to the bottom.

49:42.479 --> 49:43.981 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
And...

49:43.981 --> 49:45.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You mean the
painting literally sort of
falls?

49:45.683 --> 49:46.250 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

49:46.250 --> 49:47.785 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TON WILMERING: Sags, exactly.

49:47.785 --> 49:51.121 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: It
sags. I see. I see.

49:51.121 --> 49:54.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So what are you doing here?
You're taking a picture of the
painting.

49:54.124 --> 49:57.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAFFAELLA FONTANA, Physicist:
Yes, we're trying to measure not
only the visible image of a

49:57.194 --> 50:01.832 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
painting, but also what is
beneath the paint layer.

50:01.832 --> 50:07.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Raffaella Fontana
is a physicist using
multispectrum scanning
techniques to

50:07.705 --> 50:12.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
peer beneath the surface of
paintings, a noninvasive way to
create complex models of their
many

50:12.409 --> 50:14.478 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
layers.

50:14.478 --> 50:19.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAFFAELLA FONTANA: And then
there are conservators and
restorers that pick up our data
and decide

50:19.783 --> 50:23.754 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
how to work on a painting.

50:23.754 --> 50:29.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One of those
restorers is Ciro Castelli using
knowledge and tools that date

50:29.260 --> 50:34.465 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
back further than the
Renaissance masterworks
themselves. He was a young
carpenter just

50:34.465 --> 50:38.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
beginning his career when the
flood hit. He helped removed mud
and then began to work

50:38.235 --> 50:41.305 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with expert wood restorers.

50:41.305 --> 50:45.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CIRO CASTELLI, Restorer (through
translator): To work on wood,
you need to know it. Knowing

50:45.209 --> 50:49.346 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how wood reacts is vital for
restoration. We can't restore a
painting if we don't know

50:49.346 --> 50:53.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about its structure. Woodcraft
spans more than centuries. It's
millennia.

50:53.584 --> 50:58.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Castelli came out
of retirement to work on the
Vasari paneling. And a key

50:58.923 --> 51:03.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
goal of this project is that he
not only apply his special
knowledge to this individual
work,

51:03.727 --> 51:07.698 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
but also train a new
generation of restorers.

51:07.698 --> 51:11.502 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CIRO CASTELLI (through
translator): Working with
younger people is a way to stay
young,

51:11.502 --> 51:16.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not just as far as the spirit is
concerned, but in the activity
itself as well. Working

51:16.807 --> 51:19.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with younger people means
passing on our knowledge, which
benefits those of us who provide
the

51:19.710 --> 51:21.679 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
knowledge too.

51:21.679 --> 51:26.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There is concern
here, amid Italy's continuing
economic troubles, about

51:26.884 --> 51:33.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
funding to train and employ this
next generation. Still, as the
50th anniversary of Florence's

51:33.123 --> 51:37.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Great Flood approaches, Cecilia
Frosinini hopes to have the Last
Supper finished and

51:37.828 --> 51:41.365 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
returned to the
Santa Croce Museum.

51:41.365 --> 51:45.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CECILIA FROSININI: Giving back
this painting to the city is a
very important symbolic act.

51:45.035 --> 51:48.405 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you're
going to make it in time?

51:48.405 --> 51:55.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CECILIA FROSININI: We are
really, really going for this
deadline. I think we will make
it.

51:55.279 --> 51:59.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: From Florence,
Italy, I'm Jeffrey Brown for the
"PBS NewsHour."

51:59.850 --> 52:04.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You can go behind
the scenes, even more online,
where you will find producer

52:04.221 --> 52:09.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Frank Carlson's photo essay on
the OPD and the Santa Croce
Museum.

52:09.126 --> 52:14.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, tomorrow, Jeff returns with
a second story of Culture at
Risk in Italy, this time

52:14.598 --> 52:30.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a dying hilltop town that's
coming back to life through
engineering and tourism.

52:30.247 --> 52:35.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" online, we pay
tribute to "Joy of Painting"
master Bob Ross by trying

52:35.886 --> 52:42.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to imitate his happy trees in a
painting of our own. The late
PBS star's official YouTube

52:42.292 --> 52:47.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
channel released his very first
episode from 1983, and we
decided to try to follow along

52:47.931 --> 52:50.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with his master class.

52:50.701 --> 52:57.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The result -- you be the judge
-- is posted on our home page,
PBS.org/NewsHour.

52:57.975 --> 53:00.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And tune in later tonight, on
"Charlie Rose," for Democratic
presidential candidate Bernie

53:00.677 --> 53:02.946 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Sanders.

53:02.946 --> 53:06.350 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's the "NewsHour" for
tonight. I'm Gwen Ifill.

53:06.350 --> 53:10.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Join us online and again here
